  "local_port": 58986,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I want to go and work abroad, dont have much of a professional degree like engineering, I have done b.a. and gniit, is there a scope. my age is 25?",
  "response": "Absolutely, there are opportunities for people with a Bachelor of Arts degree and a GNIT (Graphic Network Interface Training) certification to work abroad. While you may not have a professional degree like engineering, many countries value diverse skills and experiences. Here are some avenues you can explore:\n\n1. **Teaching English**: If you are fluent in English, you can consider teaching English as a foreign language (TEFL). Many countries offer opportunities for English teachers, and some may not require a degree specifically in education.\n\n2. **IT and Technical Roles**: With your GNIT certification, you may be eligible for entry-level jobs in IT, such as technical support, network administration, or customer service for tech companies. The tech industry often values skills and certifications over formal degrees.\n\n3. **Internships and Traineeships**: Look for internships that match your skill set. Even unpaid or low-paid internships can be valuable in gaining international experience and making professional connections.\n\n4. **Work Visa Programs**: Some countries have working holiday or visa programs for young people that allow you to work in various sectors. Research options available in countries like Canada, Australia, New Zealand, and certain European nations.\n\n5. **Hospitality and Service Industry**: Many countries have a high demand for workers in hospitality, tourism, and the service industry. If you are open to starting in these fields, there are opportunities that can lead to more permanent positions.\n\n6. **Freelancing and Remote Work**: Explore freelancing opportunities in areas like graphic design, content writing, or other online services. Many companies hire remote workers, which allows you to work from anywhere.\n\n7. **Networking and Job Fairs**: Attend job fairs, networking events, and workshops related to your field of interest. Engaging with professionals and recruiters can open doors to job opportunities.\n\n8. **Further Education or Certification**: Consider pursuing additional certifications or short courses that could enhance your employability in specific fields, such as digital marketing, project management, or coding.\n\nBefore moving abroad, ensure you understand the visa requirements and job market conditions of the country you are interested in. Taking steps to gain relevant work experience and improve your skills will also improve your employability. Good luck!",
